## Graph vs registry

- **Roadmap graph:** `roadmap/manifest.json` plus included `*.json` chunks under `roadmap/` (merged in `includes` order). Edits to the roadmap structure happen in those JSON files. In **this** repository, `tests/fixtures/specy_road_dogfood/roadmap/` is the dogfood **test fixture** used for validation and sample data; consumer projects keep `roadmap/` at their repo root after `specy-road init project`.
- **`roadmap/registry.yaml`:** Active work registration (codename, branch, touch zones) only — not part of the merged graph.

## Roadmap-linked consumer/fixture work (must follow)

- Before implementing, read `docs/git-workflow.md`.
- Use branch naming `feature/rm-<codename>` for roadmap work.
- Follow the **registration discipline** in `roadmap/registry.yaml` — register on the integration branch, then `feature/rm-*`; remove before merge. Use `tests/fixtures/specy_road_dogfood/roadmap/registry.yaml` only for work that specifically exercises or updates the dogfood fixture.
- Respect **touch zones**; avoid changing files outside them unless required.

## Prefer the repo’s native protocol

Consumer projects coordinate via `roadmap/registry.yaml` (not an ad-hoc status markdown table). The dogfood fixture mirrors that contract for tests and samples, but it is not the canonical toolkit product roadmap. For automated task pickup, see **`015-do-next-registry-publish.mdc`** — registration must reach the **remote** integration branch by default (`do-next-available-task`).

